\section{Numerical solution in a wide range of the coupling}

The QSC can be very efficiently solved numerically with essentially arbitrary precision at finite values of the coupling and all other parameters.
The general method, which is also applicable here, was developed in \cite{Gromov:2015wca}.
We have used it to generate numerical values for the quark--anti-quark potential in a wide range of the 't Hooft coupling
with $\sim 20$ digits precision. Our method works well for arbitrary real $\theta$, but we decided to focus on the case $\theta=0$. Our numerical data is listed in Appendix \ref{sec:numdata}. A plot of our results is shown on Fig. \ref{numfig}.

